1 (b) A representative of an [employer] employee organization, as defined in
2 NRS [288.400] 288.040, that represents peace officers [;] or a labor organization,
3 as defined in NRS 288.048, that represents peace officers;
4 (c) A resource officer with a behavioral health background; [and]
5 (d) A representative from a state law enforcement agency, including, without
6 limitation, the Department of Public Safety or the Department of Corrections [.] ;
7 and
8 (e) A representative of firefighters from a local government employer, as
9 defined in NRS 288.060.
10 3. The Task Force shall:
11 (a) Review the existing policies of this State concerning personal wellness
12 initiatives that account for the mental and physical health of firefighters, peace
13 officers and other law enforcement personnel; and
14 (b) Recommend personal wellness initiatives for state and local law
15 enforcement agencies [.] and fire departments.
16 4. The members of the Task Force serve without compensation.
17 5. Each member of the Task Force who is an officer or employee of the State
18 or a local government must be relieved from his or her duties without loss of
19 regular compensation so that the member may prepare for and attend meetings of
20 the Task Force and perform any work necessary to carry out the duties of the Task
21 Force in the most timely manner practicable. A state agency or local government
22 shall not require an officer or employee who is a member of the Task Force to make
23 up the time the member is absent from work to carry out his or her duties as a
24 member, and shall not require the member to take annual vacation or compensatory
25 time for the absence.
26 6. The Task Force shall, at its first meeting, elect a Chair and Vice Chair from
27 among its members.
28 7. The Task Force shall meet upon the call of the Chair or a majority of the
29 members of the Task Force.
30 8. A majority of the members of the Task Force constitutes a quorum for the
31 transaction of business, and a majority of those members present at the meeting is
32 sufficient for any official action taken by the Task Force.
33 9. The Task Force may apply for and accept any gift, donation, bequest, grant
34 or other source of money to carry out the duties of the Task Force.
35 10. The Task Force shall prepare and submit a written report to the Director
36 of the Legislative Counsel Bureau for transmittal to the Senate and Assembly
37 Standing Committees on Government Affairs for the 84th Session of the
38 Legislature. The report must include, without limitation, a summary of the work
39 and recommendations of the Task Force.
40 Sec. 2. The members of the Purple Ribbon Task Force on Firefighter and
41 Peace Officer Wellness must be appointed pursuant to section 1 of this act not later
42 than October 1, 2025.
43 Sec. 3. This act becomes effective on July 1, 2025, and expires by limitation
44 on June 30, 2027.

